{"headline": "Don\u2019t just brace for another stock-market nosedive \u2014 welcome it - MarketWatch", "author": "Barbara Kollmeyer", "tick": "AAPL", "link": "https://www.marketwatch.com/story/brace-for-another-nose-dive-for-stocks-and-welcome-it-2018-02-15", "text": "Published: Critical information for the U.S. trading day By In what would last week have seemed like a Wall Street miracle, stocks are hard at work on their fifth up day in a row this morning. The Teflon equity market we\u2019ve known and loved resurfaced yesterday as it marched onward and upward, past inflation data and a pop higher in the 10-year Treasury yield nearer the The VIX is under 20.  The only problem is that it all looks a little too easy, like a \u201cScooby-Doo\u201d mystery that\u2019s all squared away in mere minutes. Ruh-roh? At this rates.. the 10 year will break 3% this week. I honestly have no idea how ANYONE could be bullish SPX other than the standard chaser... ( it went up 2 days.. its bullish...or  it went down 2 days I am bearish ) nonsense.. There are some doubts that equities can just sail on upward from here, end of story. Among them is our , which comes from CFRA\u2019s chief investment strategist Sam Stovall, who says the S&P 500 \u201cwill likely have to retest its recent low.\u201d That low came last Thursday, when the S&P careened down to 2,532.69 before snapping back. As Stovall and others have pointed out, the index didn\u2019t break its 200-day moving average, which helped it then slingshot upward more than 6% over the next four trading days. However, the reason a retest can\u2019t be avoided is \u201crecoveries from sharp selloffs require reassurances,\u201d the CFRA strategist says. In other words, investors will need proof that the bounce was for real. The good news? That pullback will \u201cpresent a second buying opportunity, rather than usher in a new bear market, since we don\u2019t see recession on the horizon,\u201d says Stovall. A similar view comes from technical analyst Mark Arbeter, who says there\u2019s more than a \u201c50/50 chance we rollover and test (within 1% to 2%) the recent lows.\u201d A V-shaped bottom is unlikely, \u201cas there was a fair amount of technical damage to a lot of stocks,\u201d the Arbeter Investments president tells clients. The Dow is cruising above 25,000 for the first time in two weeks, while the S&P and Nasdaq are also climbing. Asian stocks matched Wall Street\u2019s prior ride higher with , though several markets there are closed for the Lunar New Year holiday. European stocks  are also The dollar is getting mugged again, crude is up a bit, but . Gold is flat. The yield on the 10-year Treasury  is right at 2.923%. See the column for the latest action, and check out . Bitcoin \u2014 or as Charlie Munger calls it \u2014 is taking aim at $10,000.  It\u2019s been quite a ride down for the dollar against the yen recently, and it looks like the same is on tap for Thursday. Our comes from London Capital Group\u2019s head of research, Jasper Lawler, whose chart below shows how the yen has broken out of its long-term trading range to hit a 15-month high recently. \u201cThe current bout of dollar weakness could still stumble, particularly as EURUSD and GBPUSD approach multi-year peaks at 1.25 and 1.43 respectively. But the breakout in the yen skews the risks in favour of another leg lower in the buck,\u201d says Lawler. Cisco is cruising higher on signs it . It\u2019s hovering at post-2000 highs in premarket after its earnings and outlook topped estimates.    TripAdvisor is soaring after . Applied Materials is up a bit on a .   is up after results, and Shake Shack is coming after the close. As well, Kraft Heinz is due to release a post-merger update after the bell. It\u2019s 13-F time, which means investors can peek inside the portfolios of big institutional managers, though the info is from the fourth quarter. Sometimes shares mentioned react. Among the highlights,   added Apple and Teva shares and cut a stake in IBM .  upped exposure to Micron , Facebook , Apple and Bank of America , and made bets on Caesars and .  added to a Brighthouse stake and took a small Twitter position. Pretty much every major 13F filing thus far: buy either , , or . The end. Amazon and Bank of America may be teaming up on lending, . Healthier Happy Meals? McDonald\u2019s sets that as .  Data out so far have shown , while inflation components of the Empire State and Philly Fed indexes . Industrial output . Still to come, a home-builder index. 18 \u2014 That\u2019s how many school shootings the U.S. has suffered so far in 2018, according to . The death toll from Wednesday\u2019s in Broward County, Fla., stands at 17, with many more injured. Everytown\u2019s map above shows the locations of the 290 school shootings since 2013, as of Feb. 8. \"Everyone predicted it,\" a student said about the shooting. I hope ever member of Congress saw this interview Melissa Falkowski, teacher at Marjory Stoneman Douglas explains how well prepared they were and how many times they drilled for this and still there was nothing they can do She breaks down when she begs Congress to do something Chaos times 50? Reince Priebus Here\u2019s the salary to make everyone happy \u2014 Radio announcer  trip up at the Winter Olympics U.K. officials say last summer Child screams for eight hours       , , Barbara Kollmeyer is an editor for MarketWatch in Madrid. Follow her on Twitter @bkollmeyer. Barbara Kollmeyer is an editor for MarketWatch in Madrid. Follow her on Twitter @bkollmeyer. Join the conversation Copyright \u00a9 2018 MarketWatch, Inc.  All rights reserved. By using this site you agree to the , , and .", "source": "https://www.marketwatch.com/"}
{"headline": "Apple's stock surges toward 5th-straight gain after Buffett boosts take, upbeat research data - MarketWatch", "author": "Tomi Kilgore", "tick": "AAPL", "link": "https://www.marketwatch.com/story/apples-stock-surges-toward-5th-straight-gain-after-buffett-boosts-take-upbeat-research-data-2018-02-15", "text": "Published: By Shares of Apple Inc. surged 3.1% in midday trade Thursday, putting it on track for a fifth-straight gain, after Warren Buffett's Berkshire Hathaway Inc. disclosed a larger stake in the technology giant, and after an upbeat research note on smartphone marketshare. The stock has now run up 11.2% since it closed at a four-month low on Feb. 7. Late Wednesday, that it owned 165.3 million shares of Apple, or about 3.3% of the shares outstanding, as of Dec. 31, up 23.3% from what it owned on Sept. 30. Separately, famed billionaire David Tepper's hedge fund Appaloosa LP more than tripled its Apple bet to 4.6 million shares. Separately, Strategy Analytics said Apple captured a record 51% of global smartphone revenue share during fourth quarter. Apple generated $61 billion in smartphone revenue during the quarter, Strategy Analytics said, more than triple the $19 billion generated by Samsung Electronics Co. Ltd. Apple shares have gained 2.1% over the past three months, while the Dow Jones Industrial Average has climbed 7.7%. Copyright \u00a9 2018 MarketWatch, Inc.  All rights reserved. By using this site you agree to the , , and .", "source": "https://www.marketwatch.com/"}
